##* {{RQ:Fry Liar|page=10|passage=The great advantage of English [[public school]] life lies of course in the quality of tutelage it provides. Adrian had received a decent and broad English education in the area of his loins. {{...}} He had quickly happened upon the truth which many lonely contemporaries would never discover, the truth that everybody, simply everybody, was panting for '''it''' and could, with patience, be ''shown'' that they were panting for '''it'''. So Adrian grabbed what was to hand and had the time of his life genitally ‚Äì focusing exclusively on his own gender of course, for this was 1973 and girls had not yet been invented.}}
# {{lb|en|uncountable}} [[sex appeal|Sex appeal]], especially that which goes beyond physical appearance.
#* {{quote-text|en|year=1904|author=Rudyard Kipling|title=Mrs Bathurst|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110530022236/http://www.readbookonline.net/readOnLine/8678
|passage='Tisn't beauty, so to speak, nor good talk necessarily. It's just '''It'''. Some women'll stay in a man's memory if they once walked down a street}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1927|author={{w|Dorothy Parker}}|chapter=Madame Glyn Lectures on 'It,' with Illustrations|title=The New Yorker|date_published=1927-11-26|newversion=republished in|title2=The Portable Dorothy Parker|editor2=Brendan Gill|year2=1976|pages2=464-468|publisher2=Penguin|location2=New York|passage=And she had '''It'''. '''It''', hell; she had Those.}}
# {{non-gloss|The impersonal pronoun, used as a placeholder for a delayed subject, or less commonly, object; known as the [[dummy pronoun]] (according to some definitions), [[anticipatory it|anticipatory ''it'']] or, more formally in linguistics, a [[syntactic expletive]]. The delayed subject is commonly a ''to''-infinitive, a gerund, or a noun clause introduced by a [[:Category:English subordinating conjunctions|subordinating conjunction]].}}
#: {{ux|en|'''It''' is easy to see how she would think that.}} (with the infinitive clause headed by ''to see'')
#* {{RQ:Dickens Bleak House|text="I know now!" said I. "I have seen this in your face a long while."<br>"No; have you really, my dear?" said he. "What a Dame Durden '''it''' is to read a face!"}}
#: {{ux|en|'''It''' was felt that I'd be the [[right man]] for the job.}}
#: {{ux|en|I find '''it''' odd that you would say that.}} (with the noun clause introduced by ''that'')
#: {{ux|en|'''It''' is hard seeing you so sick.}} (with the gerund ''seeing'')
#: {{ux|en|He saw to '''it''' that everyone would vote for him.}} (with the noun clause introduced by ''that'')
#: {{ux|en|'''It''' is not clear if the report was true.}} (with the noun clause introduced by ''if'')
#: {{ux|en|She made '''it''' clear what she expected by the weekend, which made '''it''' a problem to juggle her and other customers' jobs at the same time.}} 
# [[all|All]] or the [[end]]; something after which there is no more.
#: {{ux|en|Are there more students in this class, or is this '''it'''?}}
#: {{ux|en|That's '''it'''‚ÄîI'm not going to any more candy stores with you.}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} {{n-g|Followed by an omitted and understood relative pronoun}}: That which; [[what]].
#* {{quote-text|en|year=1643|author=w:Thomas Browne|title=Religio Medici|section=II.2
|passage=In briefe, I am content, and what should providence add more? Surely this is '''it''' [= it which] wee call Happinesse, and this doe I enjoy [...].}}

